# agent-context-kit workflow

This project uses **agent-context-kit** in **Cursor**: layered docs under `docs/agent/` plus an optional **Toolshed** MCP server (`manifest.yaml`). Follow this every session.

## Cursor alignment (same stack as “power user” write-ups)

- **Keep ambient context small:** short imperative [`CLAUDE.md`](../../CLAUDE.md); long standards live in `docs/human/` and load via Toolshed `get_rules` or path-scoped rules — see **`docs/human/agent-context-power-user-stack.md`** (*Cursor alignment*). **In the agent-context-kit monorepo** (no `docs/human/` at repo root), use **`template/docs/human/agent-context-power-user-stack.md`**.
- **Path-scoped rules:** add `.cursor/rules/*.mdc` with **`globs`** and **`alwaysApply: false`** for directory-specific conventions; keep **`alwaysApply: true`** only for repo-wide workflows (like this file).
- **Plan before risky work:** use **Cursor Plan mode** ([docs](https://www.cursor.com/docs/agent/modes)) for multi-file or high-uncertainty tasks; align plans with `docs/agent/context-policy.md` (L1/L2).
- **Few MCP servers:** Cursor **Settings → MCP** — prefer Toolshed plus a small set of justified servers (each adds tool schemas to context).
- **Hooks (optional):** [Cursor Hooks](https://docs.cursor.com/agent/hooks) — **`.cursor/hooks.json`** (created by **`context-kit init`**, starts with an empty `hooks` object) and **`.cursor/hooks/README.md`**; add scripts under **`.cursor/hooks/`** when needed. Pair with `manifest.yaml` **guardrails** and Toolshed approval tools where configured.

## If Toolshed MCP is connected

At the **start** of a substantive session (or before a large change):

1. Call **`get_project_identity`** — L0: values, architecture primer, glossary.
2. Call **`get_guardrails`** — blocked actions, approval requirements, allowed domains (if configured).
3. Before **coding or review**, call **`get_rules`** (optional `standard` if you only need one, e.g. `testing`).
4. For **feature work**, call **`list_registry`**, then **`get_spec`** with the feature `name` — do **not** load every feature spec.
5. For **terminology**, use **`lookup_glossary`** before naming new APIs or types.
6. For **prompt templates**, use **`list_prompts`** / **`get_prompt`** when relevant.
7. Check **`get_learnings`** before recommending patterns that might repeat past mistakes.
8. Use **`search_context`** or **`validate_context`** when you need to locate or verify docs paths.

**Persisting changes** (only if the user expects repo updates): **`add_learning`**, **`add_glossary_term`**, **`update_feature_status`**.

If a tool fails (missing file), say so briefly and continue with what you can read from the repo.

## If MCP is not available

Read in order: `docs/agent/values.md`, `docs/agent/architecture-primer.md`, `docs/agent/glossary.md`, then `docs/agent/context-policy.md`, then `docs/agent/key-learnings.md` as needed. Use `docs/features/` only for the feature you are working on. Read `guardrails` in `manifest.yaml` if present.

## Discipline

- Prefer **one** clarifying question when scope is unclear; do not dump full specs back in replies.
- Match existing code style; avoid unrelated files in the same diff.
- Honour `docs/agent/context-policy.md` (L1) for token and review rules.
